@@cHISTORY@@W

The term Crusader appears in Solar Court records as a campaign-honor title
for warriors who served successive engagements without rotation, accruing
field honors in place of relief. It predates both the Knight academies
formalized under the Iron Reformation and the dueling courts where the
Swordsman tradition was codified. The convergence of those two paths was
forged during the Ash-and-Iron Decades, when Midgaard's militarization
drove Knight and Swordsman training into the same reserve depots. The two
traditions had long existed in competitive tension -- formation discipline
against individual momentum, controlled body-strikes against escalating
blade pressure -- but campaigns during the Ashfall aftermath proved
repeatedly that the most effective fighters could do both. Informal cross-
training units calling themselves Crusader Corps arose within the depots,
deliberately reclaiming the old campaign title. Their doctrine: chain the
Knight's body-strikes into the Swordsman's building momentum, and the
accumulated force exceeds what either path sustains alone.

@@cCRUSADER@@W

Crusaders are battlefield zealots forged from @@cKnight@@W discipline and
@@cSwordsman@@W momentum. Where others fight to survive, Crusaders fight to
overwhelm: chaining relentless martial pressure into decisive finishing blows.

To become a Crusader, you follow the adept path tied to @@cKnight@@W and
@@cSwordsman@@W remort progression.

@@cPassive class advantages@@W
Crusader grants always-on combat scaling as adept levels rise:

  1) @@wCombo-skill damage bonus@@W
     - Crusader increases damage for Crusader-relevant remort/adept combo
       attacks (notably @@wholystrike@@W and @@wfleche@@W, plus other remort/adept
       entries in that family).
     - Scaling: +5% damage per Crusader adept level (up to +100% at 20).

  2) @@wExtra attack round@@W
     - Having any Crusader adept level grants an additional melee hit in the
       multi-hit calculation.

@@cUnique Crusader mechanics@@W
  * @@wCrusader stance@@W is available once the adept path is active.
  * @@wAnti Magic Shell@@W is learned at Crusader level 2.
  * Crusader uses @@wStrength@@W as its adept prime attribute and follows a
    heavy melee-oriented adept growth profile.

@@cCrusader reincarnation bonus@@W
Each Crusader adept reincarnation grants an additional passive bonus:

  * @@wCombo-family strike damage@@W: +2% per Crusader adept reincarnation for
    punch, kick, knee, headbutt, charge, holystrike, and fleche.
  * At @@w20+ Crusader adept reincarnations@@W, combo capacity gains +1 slot
    when combo progression is active.

In short: Crusader is the pressure-and-finisher adept, rewarding players who
chain weapon and body-strike sequences into explosive melee bursts.

